Hi,

Le 10/05/2010 08:53, ido kibovito a ķcrit :
> thanks for your input. If you could give me some info on that XML
> (structure, needed information, example)

On a GNU/Linux OS, you can find the database files in
/usr/share/ddccontrol-db/monitor/.

> or even a how to if you guys
> have something like that, would probably help a lot.

Unfortunately, we don't have such a document. It is actually in our
plans to improve the way users can add monitors to the database. Right
now, we just get the output of the command by e-mail on the mailing
list, and then we have to do everything by ourselves.

> I'll see what I can do anyway.

Basically, when you look at the output of the command you posted, you
can see that ddccontrol failed to parse a specific XML file
(SAM027F.xml). The file doesn't exist, and for your monitor to be
supported, you have to create the file.

To do that, have a look at the SAMlcd.xml file to see what the tags and
attributes are.

The controls you have to add are located in the vcp() group in the output.
In your case: vcp(04 05 08 10 12 14(02 03 0A 0B) 16 18 1A 60(01 03) 87
B0(01 02) B6 C6 C8 C9 D6(01 04) DC(01 02 03 04 05 06 F0) DF F0(00 01 02
03) F3(00 01) F2 )

Here is a starting point for your file :

file SAM027F.xml
-----------------------
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!--- "Standard" Samsung controls, 87, CA, CC, E2, F5 are useful but
usually not in caps -->
<monitor name="Samsung SyncMaster 226BW (LCD)">

        <caps add="(vcp(04 05 08 10 12 14(02 03 0A 0B) 16 18 1A 60(01
03) 87 B0(01 02) B6 C6 C8 C9 D6(01 04) DC(01 02 03 04 05 06 F0) DF F0(00
01 02 03) F3(00 01) F2 ))"/>
        <include file="SAMlcd.xml"/>
	<control id="some_control" address="0xF3">
		<value id="first_value" value="0" />
		<value id="second_value" value="1" />
	</control>
</monitor>
-----------------------------

You should of course modify the control section I added, based on the
options of your monitor. Basically, each control corresponds to an
option in the OSD. You'll have to guess which control maps to which
function in the OSD based on the number of options.

In the output, you'll notice that some of the controls are already
mapped to an OSD function. That is because some of the controls are
defined by VESA. The other controls have to be mapped with a guess.

Once you've done that you can test your file by running the gddccontrol,
and changing the

We understand that this is a lot of work, and it is far from ideal, and
we have to think of a better way to do that.

> When is the next freeze for this stuff?

Nothing's planned so far. The project was dead when I took over a couple
of months ago. And it still isn't very active (only 2 developers), but
we'll get to it as soon as we have a bit of time.

> So it can go right in if I actually can do it in time.

No worries about that!

Thanks for your help and support

William


